        <div n="160-12W2">
          <head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-1">
            <lg n="1" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote">
              <l n="1" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1">TO THE LORD TREASURER OXFORD.&#13;</l>
            </lg>
          </head>
          <head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-2">
            <lg n="1" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote">
              <l n="1" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1">1710.</l>
            </lg>
          </head>
          <head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-3">
            <lg n="1" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote">
              <l n="1" xml:id="spp-160-12W2-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1">I<hi rend="small-caps">N</hi> these free, and yet complimentary verses, Swift cautions Oxford against his greatest political error, that affection of mystery, and wish of ingrossing the whole management of public affairs, which first disgusted, and then alienated, Harcourt and Bolingbroke. On this point our author has spoken very fully in the Free Thoughts upon the present State of Affairs.</l>
            </lg>
          </head>
          <lg n="1">
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-1" n="1">A<hi rend="small-caps">TLAS</hi>, we read in ancient song,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-2" n="2">Was so exceeding tall and strong,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-3" n="3">He bore the skies upon his back,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-4" n="4">Just as the pedlar does his pack;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-5" n="5">But, as the pedlar overpress'd</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-6" n="6">Unloads upon a stall to rest,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-7" n="7">Or, when he can no longer stand,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-8" n="8">Desires a friend to lend a hand;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-9" n="9">So Atlas, lest the ponderous spheres</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-10" n="10">Should sink, and fall about his ears,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-11" n="11">Got Hercules to bear the pile,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-12" n="12">That he might sit and rest awhile</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-13" n="13">Yet Hercules was not so strong,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-14" n="14">Nor could have borne it half so long.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-15" n="15">Great statesmen are in this condition;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-16" n="16">And Atlas is a politician,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-17" n="17">A premier minister of state;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-18" n="18">Alcides one of second rate.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-19" n="19">Suppose then Atlas ne'er so wise;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-20" n="20">Yet, when the weight of kingdoms lies</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-21" n="21">Too long upon his single shoulders,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-160-12W2-line-22" n="22">Sink down he must, or find upholders.</l>
          </lg>
